The dependent variable was measured through teacher-made maps. Students labeled sections of the United States after a variety' of activities using the computer software ‘‘States & Traits’* developed by Designware (1984). There were four section maps  (1) Western United States, (2) Central United States, (3) Southeast United States, and (4) Northeast United States. The pretest was also the posttest in the same format. Students were given a numbered map of the United States, and an answer sheet listing all the states. The test was to place the number corresponding to the appropriate state on the answer sheet.

out_desc_tool: Results coded using the adjusted M achievement total scores. The tests were criterion-referenced based on the districts social studies curriculum. The pretest was made up of thirty multiple choice questions taken from the test bank which accompanied the textbook. The 30 questions were selected to assess the students prior knowledge of the unit objectives and represented a variety of difficulty levels. The posttest was made up of the same thirty multiple choice questions as the pretest (the questions were shuffled prior to the posttest), in addition to a series of identification, short answer and essay questions. All questions included in the posttest were based on content covered in the classroom lesson plans, and were adapted directly from the test bank prov ided with the textbook.

out_desc_tool: Posttest means and SD's for a mathematics test. Pearson Benchmark pretest/posttest served as the data collection tool for this study. This computerized 16-item multiple choice test is used by the participating school district to document students’ mathematical achievement. The assessment covered the Georgia Performance Standards set forth by the State of Georgia for second grade students during the fourth nine weeks of the school year. The curriculum map that designated the content that was covered is located in Appendix A. Specifically, the test covered the following curriculum standards  (a) understanding multiplication as repeated addition  (b) using repeated addition, arrays, and counting my multiples to correctly multiply one-digit numbers and construct a multiplication table  and (c) using a multiplication table to determine the product of two numbers.

out_desc_tool: The primary outcome at the end of the study was science attainment, measured using one paper of the science Key Stage 3 SATs (2009 Tier 3-6 Paper 2). The KS3 science SATs test was designed to be administered to students towards the end of Year 9, when they were due to have completed the KS3 curriculum. The test was designed to cover the full range of content, including scientific enquiry, life processes, materials, and physical processes. Because this test was being administered at the end of Year 8, when some schools would only be part-way through the KS3 curriculum (schools usually take 2–3 years to complete KS3) we administered the easier form of the test (Tier 3-6).

The post test contained 7 fact, 13 application, 10 generalization and 10 problem-solving questions

The test included a story of about 700 words followed by five open-ended questions. Students were asked to analyse the text, to write up the ending of the story, to put the key theme in an abstract, to identify the implications of the story, and to pose and answer self-generated questions. These open-ended tasks involved both reading and writing, and were used to examine the extent to which the children were able to construct meaning based on the text passages. Students were not required to write down correct words or complete sentences, and their responses were evaluated in terms of qualitative understanding and not in terms of how many points they had included.

TOAM procedure was used to assess students' achievement in mathematics at the beginning and at the end of the study. TOAM scores are presented by two digit numbers in which the tens digit presents the equivalent year level and the unit digit presents the equivalent month level within that year. The norms were defined by the Israeli Ministry of Education.

This test probes particularly the mental macrostructure of expository texts.
